com.pb.sawdust.util.collections

Interface SetDeque<E>

  • Type Parameters:
    E - The type of the elements held by this collection.
    All Superinterfaces:
    java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.Deque<E>, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Queue<E>, java.util.Set<E>, SetQueue<E>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractSetDeque, LinkedSetList

    public interface SetDeque<E>
extends SetQueue<E>, java.util.Deque<E>
    A SetDeque is a deque which can contain no repeated values. Though it implements both the Deque and Set interface, it is intended to be used as a deque which is constrained to be a set, rather than a set which is a deque. The caveats and assumptions mentioned in the SetQueue interface apply here as well; this interface adds more force* methods which refer to the Deque interface.

      • forceAddFirst

        void forceAddFirst(E element)
        Inserts the specified element at the front of this setdeque if it is possible to do so immediately without violating capacity restrictions. If the element already exists in this setdeque its previous position will be removed. When using a capacity-restricted setdeque, it is generally preferable to use method forceOfferFirst(E).
        Parameters:
        element - The element to be added to the setdeque.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if the element cannot be added at this time due to capacity restrictions.

      • forceOfferFirst

        boolean forceOfferFirst(E element)
        Inserts the specified element at the front of this setdeque unless it would violate capacity restrictions. If the element already exists in this setdeque its previous position will be removed. When using a capacity-restricted setdeque, this method is generally preferable to the forceAddFirst(E) method, which can fail to insert an element only by throwing an exception.
        Parameters:
        element - The element to be added to the setdeque.
        Returns:
        true if this setdeque has changed as a result of this operation, false otherwise.

      • forcePush

        void forcePush(E element)
        Pushes an element onto the stack represented by this deque (in other words, at the head of this deque) if it is possible to do so immediately without violating capacity restrictions, returning true upon success and throwing an IllegalStateException if no space is currently available. This method is equivalent to forceAddFirst(E).
        Parameters:
        element - The element to be added to the setdeque.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if the element cannot be added at this time due to capacity restrictions.
